The Economics of Violence
KOPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine and elsewhere are constantly in the news and therefore many would probably say war.
Yet this turns out to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It goes without saying that every war and violence would be gladly ended, just as we would like to put an end to poverty, hunger and global warming and provide all people with access to education.
Yet given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We need to set priorities and for this purpose one can use an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to assess which goals, in their view, would be the wisest.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of resources that would otherwise, for example, flow into the fight against hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University, violence in society – murders and especially violence against women and children – presents a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die from interpersonal violence, and for every two fighters who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries report murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization describes as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs a person's life and society 9.1 million US dollars.
Measured against the national income worldwide, this form of violent crime alone costs 1.7% of the global gross social product (GDP).
Naturally, this is not a direct financial loss for the global economy, but rather a way of expressing the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies around the world would be better off in a way that can be measured as 1.7% of GDP.
Comparing this to the clearly lower costs of civil wars, which amount to about 0.2% of global GDP.
This is still far less than the greatest source of violence altogether: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence by their partners or family members in the past year.
This includes women who were beaten, forced into early marriage, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and subjected to female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs of violence by partners alone amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars, or 5.2% of global GDP.
The second largest source of violence is child abuse, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of what constitutes child abuse varies across cultures, but roughly 15% of children experience what the UN describes as severe physical punishment each month.
These include hitting in the face, on the head or on the ears, and a quarter of these children are hit repeatedly and as violently as possible with an object.
This suffering befalls about 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of global GDP.
A tiny fraction of international aid funds currently flows into the reduction of violence in society and into the improvement of legal systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and by individuals scream out for action to be taken.
Unfortunately, there are still few secure insights into where the limited resources should be best used.
All that can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be used more targetedly.
Large sums of aid money are allocated to "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the "crime prevention" component.
Other programs may contribute indirectly, but it is obvious that much could be improved.
Some solutions, as much is clear, work very well.
More capable social institutions can reduce child violence.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life and their physical and mental health, and reduce the costs of child welfare and legal proceedings.
A dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth 14 US dollars: it is therefore an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program named SASA! in Uganda is working.
(Kisuaheli für „Jetzt!“) dafür ein, die Auffassung zu verbreiten, dass Gewalt in der Partnerschaft inakzeptabel ist und hat dazu beigetragen, die Zahl der Fälle zu halbieren.
Das ist ein fantastisches Resultat, auch wenn dazu keine Analyse der Kosteneffizienz vorliegt.
Es gibt Beispiele aus anderen Ländern, in denen wirksame Maßnahmen ergriffen werden.
Im Jahr 1993 hat es in Bogotá 80 Morde auf je 100.000 Einwohner gegeben.
Mit einem umfassenden Ansatz – eine zeitliche Begrenzung für den Verkauf von Alkohol, die Rückeroberung des öffentlichen Raumes und Verbesserungen im Polizei- und Justizsystem – wurde die Mordrate auf 21 Opfer je 100.000 Einwohner im Jahr 2004 gesenkt.
This is still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and the findings from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of major importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on better enforcement of existing regulations showed that violent attacks could be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with the benefit outweighing the cost by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We still do not know enough, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children brings with it costs of 8 billion US dollars per year for society and thus represents a huge – and far too little noticed – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective way.
For this reason, the reduction of domestic violence should be included in the narrower selection of development goals for the world.
